with plans to have it
fully paved by, well, soon.

16:36.180 --> 16:37.693
It's carved into
the side of the mountain.

16:37.700 --> 16:40.190
Unbelievable. How many
workers they say working this?

16:40.220 --> 16:41.430
40,000.

16:41.460 --> 16:44.330
Respect for the natural world
is fundamental

16:44.360 --> 16:46.370
to Bhutan's spiritual identity.

16:46.400 --> 16:48.200
More than half the country

16:48.230 --> 16:50.060
is off-limits to development
or timbering.

16:50.090 --> 16:55.620
A whopping 50% of Bhutan's GDP
comes from hydropower.

16:55.650 --> 16:57.760
- Amazing, huh?
- So where are we?

16:57.790 --> 16:59.280
What is this place?

16:59.310 --> 17:01.800
This is the Punatsangchhu
hydropower dam.

17:01.830 --> 17:04.109
So this is one of the biggest
hydropower dams in Bhutan.

17:04.140 --> 17:05.869
It's about 1,200 megawatts.

17:05.900 --> 17:08.349
- How much is that?
- It's a lot of refrigerators.

17:08.390 --> 17:10.250
No, I heard there's gonna be

17:10.290 --> 17:11.770
a second...
Second dam further down.

17:11.810 --> 17:13.430
So they're gonna capture
power twice.

17:13.460 --> 17:15.640
If you have already
destroyed one river,

17:15.670 --> 17:17.569
you know, might as well...
Keep building-

17:17.599 --> 17:19.563
- Get the most out of it.
- Yeah, get the most out of it.

17:19.569 --> 17:21.780
Dr. Nawang Norbu
is the director of

17:21.819 --> 17:25.130
the School for Field Studies
Bhutan program.

17:25.160 --> 17:26.262
And what country's
building this?

17:26.270 --> 17:27.890
- It's mostly India.
- Do the Indians

17:27.920 --> 17:30.100
build it and then get
the power to pay it?

17:30.130 --> 17:32.100
They get the power.
We sell it to them.

17:32.140 --> 17:34.310
And then we sort of
liquidate the loans away.

17:34.350 --> 17:36.830
We have five such dams
which are operational.

17:36.860 --> 17:38.450
- Five.
- And I-I think

17:38.490 --> 17:40.390
six being constructed
at the moment.

17:40.420 --> 17:42.280
You know, obviously there's
a lot of destruction.

17:42.320 --> 17:43.840
It will stop some of the fishes

17:43.870 --> 17:45.630
from migrating up and down.

17:45.670 --> 17:47.353
You're also talking about
a lot of transmission lines.

17:47.360 --> 17:49.120
But, obviously, for Bhutan,

17:49.150 --> 17:50.640
I think when we started on

17:50.670 --> 17:52.183
the path of development,
I think we were left

17:52.190 --> 17:53.610
with few other options.

17:53.640 --> 17:55.810
And I think this was
the best thing for us to do.

17:55.850 --> 17:57.580
The water that comes
through this dam,

17:57.610 --> 17:59.300
is it an inexhaustible supply?

17:59.340 --> 18:01.820
- It's all glacial water.
- We hope so.

18:01.860 --> 18:03.620
There are many studies
which are showing

18:03.650 --> 18:05.650
that the Himalayan glaciers
will disappear

18:05.690 --> 18:08.140
in about 50 to 60 years.
Whoa. Whoa. Whoa.

18:08.170 --> 18:09.450
That's soon.
Yeah.

18:09.480 --> 18:10.760
Yeah, but nobody knows for sure.

18:10.800 --> 18:12.140
I mean, the science
is debatable.

18:12.180 --> 18:13.313
Are we talking about
the difference

18:13.320 --> 18:14.800
between 50 years and 100 years,

18:14.830 --> 18:16.693
or are we talking about whether
it's happening at all?

18:16.700 --> 18:18.523
No, it is happening.
There's no doubt about it.

18:18.530 --> 18:20.453
- Yes, there's no doubt.
- And you're not only talking

18:20.460 --> 18:21.873
about energy production but
you're also talking

18:21.880 --> 18:23.330
about agriculture.

18:23.360 --> 18:24.500
You know, you have less snow,

18:24.530 --> 18:26.360
it means you have
less water to feed.

18:26.400 --> 18:29.330
So climate change is going
to have a serious impact.

